  <h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'> How to Calculate Compound Interest </h3>
  </div>
  <strong>Compound interest</strong> is the interest added to the principal at the end of each time interval, therefore the principal 
  increases and the interest becomes greater for each successive interval.
 
  <div class="container">
  <div class="row">
<div class="col border-right border-danger">
<strong>Example 1 </strong>
<br>
Calculate the compound interest on $5000 for 2 years at 10% per annum.
<br>
<strong>Solution</strong>
<br>
<strong>The interest is added at 1 year interval.</strong>
<br>
<strong>Initial principal</strong> = $5000
<br>
<strong>1<sup>st</sup> year at 10% interest; I<sub>1</sub></strong> = <sup>(5000 x 10 x 1)</sup>&frasl;<sub>100</sub> = <strong>$500</strong>
<br>
1<sup>st</sup> year amount = $5000 + $500 = <strong>$5500</strong>
<br>
<strong>2<sup>nd</sup> year at 10% interest; I<sub>2</sub></strong> =  <sup>(5500 x 10 x 1)</sup>&frasl;<sub>100</sub> = <strong>$550</strong>
<br>
2<sup>nd</sup> year amount = $5500 + $550 = <strong>$6050</strong>
<br>
The compound interest = $6050 - $5000
<br>
The compound interest after 2 years = <strong>$1050</strong>

</div>
